114 /** Handles writing the information about found deadlock to the log files
115 and caches it for future lock_latest_err_file() calls (for example used by
116 SHOW ENGINE INNODB STATUS)
117 @param[in] trxs_on_cycle trxs causing deadlock, i-th waits for i+1-th
118 @param[in] victim_trx the trx from trx_on_cycle which will be rolled back

120 static void notify(const ut::vector<const trx_t *> &trxs_on_cycle,

122
123 private:
124 #ifdef UNIV_DEBUG
125 /** Determines if a situation in which the lock takes part in a deadlock
126 cycle is expected (as in: handled correctly) or not (say because it is on a DD
127 table, for which there is no reason to expect a deadlock and we don't handle
128 deadlocks correctly). The purpose of the function is to use it in an assertion
129 failing as soon as the deadlock is identified, to give developer a chance to
130 investigate the root cause of the situation (without such assertion, the code
131 might continue to run and either fail at later stage when the data useful for
132 debugging is no longer on stack, or not fail at all, which is risky).
133 @param[in] lock lock found in a deadlock cycle
134 @return true if we expect that this lock can take part in a deadlock cycle */
135 static bool is_allowed_to_be_on_cycle(const lock_t *lock);
136 #endif /* UNIV_DEBUG */
137
138 /** Print transaction data to the deadlock file and possibly to stderr.
139 @param trx transaction
140 @param max_query_len max query length to print */
141 static void print(const trx_t *trx, ulint max_query_len);
142
143 /** rewind(3) the file used for storing the latest detected deadlock
144 and print a heading message to stderr if printing of all deadlocks to
145 stderr is enabled. */
146 static void start_print();
147
148 /** Print lock data to the deadlock file and possibly to stderr.
149 @param lock record or table type lock */
150 static void print(const lock_t *lock);
151
152 /** Print a message to the deadlock file and possibly to stderr.
153 @param msg message to print */
154 static void print(const char *msg);
155
156 /** Prints a numbered section title to the deadlock file and possibly to
157 stderr. Numbers do not have to be unique, as they are used to identify
158 transactions on the cycle, and there are multiple sections per transaction.
159 @param[in] pos_on_cycle The zero-based position of trx on deadlock cycle
160 @param[in] title The title of the section */
161 static void print_title(size_t pos_on_cycle, const char *title);

1038 /** Checks if the (-infinity,max_old_active_id] range contains an id of
1039 a currently active transaction which has modified a record.
1040 The premise is that the caller has seen a record modified by a trx with
1041 trx->id <= max_old_active_id, and wants to know if it might be still active.
1042 It may err on the safe side.
1043
1044 @remarks
1045 The difficulties to keep in mind here:
1046 - the caller doesn't hold trx_sys mutex, nor can prevent any transaction
1047 from committing or starting before the start and after the end of execution
1048 of this function. Thus the result of this function has to be interpreted
1049 as if it could have a "one sided error", even if the return value is exact
1050 during the execution
1051 - the transactions are assigned ids from increasing sequence, but they are
1052 added to various structures like lists and shards out of order. This means
1053 that the answer this function gives only makes sense in the context that
1054 the caller already saw an effect of the trx modifying some row, which
1055 means it had to be already added to these structures. In other words,
1056 calling this function twice for the same number can give false then true.
1057 Still the false from the first call is "correct" for the purpose of the
1058 caller (as it must mean that the trx which modified the record had to be
1059 removed from the structures already, hence is not active anymore).
1060 Also the true from the second call is "correct" in that indeed some smaller
1061 transaction id had to be added to the structures meanwhile, even if it's
1062 not the one which modified the record in question - error on the safe side.
1063
1064 @param[in] max_old_active_id The end of the range inclusive. For example
1065 found in the PAGE_MAX_TRX_ID field of a
1066 header of a secondary index page.
1067 @retval false the caller may assume that if before the call it saw a
1068 record modified by trx_id, and trx_id < max_old_active_id,
1069 then it is no longer active
1070 @retval true the caller should double check in a synchronized way if
1071 the seen trx_id is still active or not
1072 */
1073 19472779 static bool can_older_trx_be_still_active(trx_id_t max_old_active_id) {

1079 NOTE: Do not be tempted to "cache" the minimum, until you also enforce that
1080 transactions are inserted to shards in a monotone order!

1991 /* A very common type of lock in InnoDB is "Next Key Lock", which is almost
1992 equivalent to two locks: Record Lock and GAP Lock separately.
1993 Thus, in case we need to wait, we check if we already own a Record Lock,
1994 and if we do, we only need the GAP Lock.
1995 We don't do the opposite thing (of checking for GAP Lock, and only requesting
1996 Record Lock), because if Next Key Lock has to wait, then it is because of a
1997 conflict with someone who locked the record, as locks on gaps are compatible
1998 with each other, so even if we have a GAP Lock, narrowing the requested mode
1999 to Record Lock will not make the conflict go away.
2000
2001 In current implementation locks on supremum are treated like GAP Locks,
2002 in particular they never have to wait for anything (unless they are Insert
2003 Intention locks, but we've ruled that out with asserts before getting here),
2004 so there is no gain in using the above "lock splitting" heuristic for locks on
2005 supremum, and reasoning becomes a bit simpler without this special case. */

4403 /** A helper function which solves a chicken-and-egg problem occurring when one
4404 needs to iterate over trx's locks and perform some actions on them. Iterating
4405 over this list requires trx->mutex (or exclusive global lock_sys latch), and
4406 operating on a lock requires lock_sys latches, yet the latching order requires
4407 lock_sys latches to be taken before trx->mutex.
4408 One way around it is to use exclusive global lock_sys latch, which heavily
4409 deteriorates concurrency. Another is to try to reacquire the latches in needed
4410 order, veryfing that the list wasn't modified meanwhile.
4411 This function performs following steps:
4412 1. releases trx->mutex,
4413 2. acquires proper lock_sys shard latch for given lock,
4414 3. reaquires trx->mutex
4415 4. executes f unless trx's locks list has changed
4416 Before and after this function following should hold:
4417 - the shared global lock_sys latch is held
4418 - the trx->mutex is held
4419 @param[in] lock the lock we are interested in
4420 @param[in] f the function to execute when the shard is latched
4421 @return true if f was called, false if it couldn't be called because trx locks
4422 have changed while relatching trx->mutex
4423 */

4453 /** Tries to release read locks of a transaction without latching the whole
4454 lock sys. This may fail, if there are many concurrent threads editing the
4455 list of locks of this transaction (for example due to B-tree pages being
4456 merged or split, or due to implicit-to-explicit conversion).
4457 It is called during XA prepare to release locks early.
4458 @param[in,out] trx transaction
4459 @param[in] only_gap release only GAP locks
4460 @return true if and only if it succeeded to do the job*/
4461 132600 [[nodiscard]] static bool try_release_read_locks_in_s_mode(trx_t *trx,
4462 bool only_gap) {
4463 /* In order to access trx->lock.trx_locks safely we need to hold trx->mutex.
4464 So, conceptually we'd love to hold trx->mutex while iterating through
4465 trx->lock.trx_locks.
4466 However the latching order only allows us to obtain trx->mutex AFTER any
4467 lock_sys latch.
4468 One way around this problem is to simply latch the whole lock_sys in exclusive
4469 mode (which also prevents any changes to trx->lock.trx_locks), however this
4470 impacts performance in appliers (TPS drops by up to 10%).
4471 Here we use a different approach:
4472 1. we extract lock from the list when holding the trx->mutex,
4473 2. identify the shard of lock_sys it belongs to,
4474 3. store the current version of trx->lock.trx_locks
4475 4. release the trx->mutex,
4476 5. acquire the lock_sys shard's latch,
4477 6. and reacquire the trx->mutex,

5809 /* This trx->mutex acquisition here is not really needed.
5810 Its purpose is to prevent a state transition between calls to trx_state_eq()
5811 and lock_rec_add_to_queue().
5812 But one can prove, that even if the state did change, it is not
5813 a big problem, because we still keep reference count from dropping
5814 to zero, so the trx object is still in use, and we hold the shard latched,
5815 so trx can not release its explicit lock (if it has any) so we will
5816 notice the explicit lock in lock_rec_has_expl.
5817 On the other hand if trx does not have explicit lock, then we would create
5818 one on its behalf, which is wasteful, but does not cause a problem, as once
5819 the reference count drops to zero the trx will notice and remove this new
5820 explicit lock. Also, even if some other trx had observed that trx is already
5821 removed from rw trxs list and thus ignored the implicit lock and decided to
5822 add its own lock, it will still have to wait for shard latch before adding
5823 her lock. However it does not cost us much to simply take the trx->mutex

6810 There are some such tables though, for which a deadlock is somewhat expected,
6811 for various reasons specific to these particular tables.
6812 So, we have a list of exceptions here:
6813
6814 innodb_table_stats and innodb_index_stats
6815 These two tables are visible to the end user, so can take part in
6816 quite arbitrary queries and transactions, so deadlock is possible.
6817 Therefore we need to allow such deadlocks, as otherwise a user
6818 could crash a debug build of a server by issuing a specific sequence of
6819 queries. DB_DEADLOCK error in dict0stats is either handled (see for
6820 example dict_stats_rename_table), or ignored silently (for example in
6821 dict_stats_process_entry_from_recalc_pool), but I am not aware of any
6822 situation in which DB_DEADLOCK could cause a serious problem.
6823 Most such queries are performed via dict_stats_exec_sql() which logs an
6824 ERROR in case of a DB_DEADLOCK, and also returns error code to the caller,
6825 so both the end user and a developer should be aware of a problem in case
6826 they want to do something about it.

6828 table_stats and index_stats
